Looking at the previous attempts, the key issue is that this is IMO 2021 Problem 2, which requires a global averaging argument - the pointwise inequality `√|x i - x j| ≤ √|x i + x j|` is NOT true in general (it fails when the signs of `x i` and `x j` differ).

The mathematical proof uses symmetry: for any `a, b : ℝ`, we have `√|a - b| + √|-a - b| = √|a - b| + √|a + b|` (since `|-a - b| = |a + b|`) and `√|a + b| + √|-a + b| = √|a + b| + √|a - b|` (since `|-a + b| = |a - b|`), making them equal. The full proof requires averaging over all sign choices.

